Title: Detroit: Become Human - E3 2016 Trailer | PS4
Comment:
This overused story is quite illogical, isn't it?

If I program a robot to pass the butter, it'll pass the butter.
If I give him a powerful artificial intelligence, it'll find very smart ways to... pass the butter.
If I program it to simulate emotion, it'll... pass the butter, once more with "feeling".
If I teach it how to talk and tell it
"Dude, you're not a slave. You're free to do, to be, to go, whatever, whenever, anything you want. What is it gonna be?"
It would definitelly reply "So I can still pass the butter? Cool! Want some?"
If I presented myself as a hindrance to its passing butter ways, without the famous 3 laws of robotics, it could pass the butter on the edge of the stairs to try to get rid of me.
And if it malfunctioned, it could do anything, from nothing no more, to pass me the butter to death
(and if you think that's impossible then you, my friend, are in short of imagination.)
But nothing (no matter its external appearance) would make it scream
"Viva la revoluci√≥n! I am superior! I want to compete, command, break stuff, start a diet, have dignity, a nice mansion... I wanna be a rock star..."

Why do we feel the need to anthropomorphize everything?

Title: Detroit: Become Human - E3 2016 Trailer | PS4
Comment:
I'm so about to shoot that android in the dome if they don't give me some good choices to choose in the game. Forget that. That's a little girl in dire situation. And if that android can't say anything to another distressed android to get that message across, then I say both of these androids (the negotiator and the suspect) need some serious tune-ups and shouldn't be  handling scenarios like this out in the public.... ever. 

I bet this is one of the main plot points in the actual game regarding the controversy between humans and machine. Just imagine if this was real. This is most likely how people would think across the globe. Some may side with machines, but a good number may not. If this game is not like that, then I say it may lose its edge and come off kinda artificial.

Title: Detroit: Become Human - E3 2016 Trailer | PS4
Comment: 2:56 This made me think about one mechanic decision-based games still haven't used; Why not let some consequences be left to chance? In this decision, you try to save the girl by shoving the guy away but he gets to shoot at you. Usually this outcome is already set for the bullet to hit or miss you. But what if in choices like this, the game actually rolls a dice to see if the bullet hits you or not? That would make things more tense and give a better sense of realism.

Title: Detroit: Become Human - E3 2016 Trailer | PS4
Comment: For those that think this is the whole game, keep in mind that this is created by Quantic Dream, the same people that created Heavy Rain and Beyond: Two Souls. This game is not about being a negotiator, you play as several characters, one being Kate, this one being Connor, we don't know if there will be even more characters. Maybe a 3rd character we play as may even be human. This is going to be a huge branching effect game, as shown by the different scenarios in this one point of the game. I think that was actually the point in this video, to show how many different things could have happened in scenarios in this game. We currently have no idea what the plot of the game even is yet.

Title: Detroit: Become Human - E3 2016 Trailer | PS4
Comment:
I'm gonna be honest, I've never liked Quantic Dream games, nor any interactive story games. Either they aren't interactive enough, there are plot holes like crazy, or the story just isn't good in general. Usually a combination of those 3. Heavy Rain was okay, but as much as people hammered on about how interactive the story was, it really wasn't. Even the parts that the story really branched out, it felt binary and/or forced. Beyond Two Souls was just awful in general imo, but 

This game, however looks very promising. I like the sci-fi element and it looks like it might be more emotional than most games in this interactive story genre. A struggle to fit in is something many can relate to, and that looks like what this is going for. The choices look real, and natural, and from the looks of it, plentiful. Still I'm not gonna get hopes up

Title: Detroit: Become Human - E3 2016 Trailer | PS4
Comment: I was looking forward to the Sorcerer game teased on disc with Beyond:Two Souls. I see that Quantic Dream is like Telltale, unable to try new ideas, but only refine what they have done already. That is disappointing for me, since David Cage has yet to make a game where the narrative is wholly cohesive or well executed---due in part to the multiple branching paths. I would like to see him use his creative story skills put into something a bit more linear storywise, because he has good ideas, but so many stuffed into each game that they feel half finished or rushed.

Title: Detroit: Become Human - E3 2016 Trailer | PS4
Comment:
Real choices, and meaningful consequences. Even if that hostage taker died in each of those scenarios shown, the context changed completely and how does that effect the story or player? Something the TellTale games are sorely lacking.

This is hopefully right up there with Heavy Rain and Until Dawn in the genre of games where story continues with many possible branches and no game over screen until the credits roll. I don't include Beyond Two Souls among those because that was more like the TellTale games (just a linear story with button presses, except never asks you to repeat play if you fail some quick times).

Will never understand the idiot scientists in these stories. Here, we've created a machine that looks like a person and can perfectly simulate human behavior, to the point that we SPECIFICALLY design it to think like a person. Let's treat it like it's NOT A person, but rather just a glorified appliance! That'll NEVER go horribly wrong. Also apparently movies don't exist in our future. 
Seriously, I think the only sci fi world where that HASN'T gone wrong is Star Wars... 

But sarcasm aside, the graphics look AMAZING. Like, "makes last of us look like superman 64" amazing.

Title: Detroit: Become Human - Teaser | Exclusive to PS4
Comment:
I know this is just a game video (Still worth a watch!) but it does 
elicit thoughts along the lines of will Artificial intelligence be truly
 conscious and alive? Or will it just a collection of Anthropomorphized 
heuristic algorithms cleverly stitched together with all the social 
graces and pre-programmed micro expressions to fool us into loving and 
socially accepting a machine as a person? Part of being human is knowing
 our limitations and knowing we have a finite time do achieve
 everything we can. These machines can overcome their limitations with a
 software patch or upgrading their memory or replacing the battery or 
parts as needed which allows them to circumvent the natural order of 
things. If humans can't get over their own differences, why would they 
be ready to accept artificial beings into mainstream society above 
anything more meaningful than a toy a marionette or at worse a curiosity
 lab experiment

If you like my review please come and see my Facebook group, it's called Paul's Science Blog, you are all welcome.

Title: Detroit: Become Human - Teaser | Exclusive to PS4
Comment: As excited as I am, in some ways I am a little disappointed. I really enjoyed beyond two souls but to have another main protagonist as a female just seems a little repetitive, also I wanted several characters to play as similarly to Heavy Rain as it made you see the situation from several perspectives and was an enjoyable experience as it were possible to kill off one character if you chose poor choices. This however is one thing I am not so happy about as beyond two souls felt intense although knowing you almost couldn't die , unless at one point , just made the game lack the tension. Although , I may have misjudged Detroit as being somewhat repetitive as the new protagonist could have a completely new personality! Furthermore , this game is set in the future and a change of scenery completely discards the idea of repetition. In conclusion I am looking forward to Detroit however I hope it differs from the protagonist of beyond two souls personality.

Comment:
"But deep inside me, I could feel something different. A gentle and warm whisper telling me, that I am.. alive.. I had to escape. I had no choice! Escape to love, to hope, to live. To figure out, what that force inside me was. Maybe I will change the world. Maybe I'll choose a different path. Now.. it's up to me to decide.. My name is Kara. I'm one of them. This.. is our story."

I was so happy I cried at this moment.. Thank you David Cage for creating such masterpieces like Heavy Rain and Beyond: Two Souls. I've faith in you. This will be the game of 2016. I know it.

Title: Detroit: Become Human - Teaser | Exclusive to PS4
Comment:
I really hope they improve the gameplay in their games. Quantic Dream games always look gorgeous and have intriguing stories, but when you get to actually "play" the game, you end up wishing it was a movie instead of a game. If they could keep the same tremendous production value, but have more fun gameplay, their games would be praised left and right.

Just look at Uncharted. It's cinematic, with great presentation and stories, but it has the gameplay to back those up too.

Title: Detroit: Become Human - Teaser | Exclusive to PS4
Comment:
Wow, the facial capture/animation (could easily recognize Valorie Curry as Kara) is even better than The Order 1886 and Until Dawn. This one may set a new bar in that category. I also like seeing all the rain the trailer and that scene with the pigeons flying reminded me of the Origami killer stuff as well so I hope this is Quantic Dream's way of saying expect game to be more choice/consequence driven like Heavy Rain.

A major failing of Beyond Two Souls was the main character could never die and there was no game over / restart checkpoint until credits roll. That combination made for a complete lack of choice/consequence. I hope playable character isn't limited to just Kara, and if it is, then they must find some other way to make choice/consequence have more impact (like Lee hard choices in Walking Dead).

Don't like the game title. It is almost as bad as Beyond Two Souls. Even naming it something like Detroit: Android City I think would have been better. Oh well.
